%I A392498 #26 Mar 03 2026 04:02:21
%S A392498 4,6,8,9,10,14,15,16,21,22,25,26,27,28,32,33,34,35,38,39,44,46,49,50,
%T A392498 51,52,55,57,58,62,63,64,65,68,69,74,75,76,77,81,82,85,86,87,91,92,93,
%U A392498 94,95,98,99,106,110,111,115,116,117,118,119,121,122,123,124,125
%N A392498 Numbers k > 1 with the smallest prime divisor p, where the sum of divisors d in the range 1 < d < k/p is less than k/p.
%C A392498 Equivalently, set D_{p}(k) = {1 < d < L : d | k}, where L = k/p. A number k is in this sequence if it is a noncomposable number (A392500) and Sum(D_{p}(k)) < L.
%C A392498 We call these numbers 'sparse numbers' because the set of admissible divisors 1 < d < k/p is too limited to form any subset summing to the largest proper divisor of k.
%C A392498 A392500 = this sequence U A392499. Thus, noncomposable numbers are either sparse or rigid.
%C A392498 No term of this sequence is prime or composable (A392440).
%C A392498 Conjecture: All perfect numbers are sparse. This conjecture is consistent with all known data (A000396).
%H A392498 Peter Luschny, <a href="https://github.com/PeterLuschny/Gists/blob/main/ComposableRigidSparse.ipynb">Composable, rigid, and sparse numbers</a>. A Python notebook.
%e A392498 The first few p-classes of sparse numbers start (note that the first term is the square of the prime):
%e A392498   p =  2 | 4, 6, 8, 10, 14, 16, ...
%e A392498   p =  3 | 9, 15, 21, 27, 33, 39, ...
%e A392498   p =  5 | 25, 35, 55, 65, 85, 95, ...
%e A392498   p =  7 | 49, 77, 91, 119, 133, 161, ...
%e A392498   p = 11 | 121, 143, 187, 209, 253, 319, ...
%o A392498 (Python)  # See also links.
%o A392498 from sympy import divisors
%o A392498 def is_sparse(n: int):
%o A392498     if n < 4: return 0
%o A392498     divs = divisors(n)[1:-1]
%o A392498     if not divs: return 0
%o A392498     if len(divs) == 1: return divs[0]
%o A392498     L = divs.pop()
%o A392498     return divs[0] if sum(divs) < L else 0
%o A392498 print([n for n in range(126) if is_sparse(n)])
%Y A392498 Cf. A392493 (p=2), A392494 (p=3), A392499 (rigid), A392500 (noncomposable), A392440 (composable), A000396 (perfect).
%K A392498 nonn
%O A392498 1,1
